{
  "What is brain drain?": "",
  "A decline in educational quality in developed nations": "",
  "The loss of information during translation": "",
  "The emigration of highly educated and skilled people from developing to developed countries": "",
  "A medical condition affecting migrants": "",
  "Brain drain refers to the emigration of highly trained professionals (doctors, engineers, scientists) from developing countries to developed countries seeking better pay and opportunities, depriving their home countries of critical human capital.": "",
  "What are remittances?": "",
  "Government aid from developed to developing countries": "",
  "Taxes paid by immigrants to their host country": "",
  "Money sent by migrants back to their families in their home country": "",
  "Fees charged by immigration authorities": "",
  "Remittances are funds that migrants send back to family members in their home country. Globally, remittances exceed $600 billion annually and for some developing countries exceed foreign aid, significantly boosting household income and national economies.": "",
  "According to Ravenstein's Laws of Migration, what is the most common type of migration?": "",
  "Rural-to-rural migration": "",
  "Short-distance migration": "",
  "Long-distance international migration": "",
  "Forced refugee movement": "",
  "Ravenstein's Laws of Migration (1885) observed that most migrants travel only short distances. Migration decreases with distance (distance decay), and the majority of long-distance migrants head toward major economic centers.": "",
  "Which global migration pattern has been dominant since the mid-20th century?": "",
  "Migration from urban to rural areas": "",
  "Migration from developing to developed countries": "",
  "Migration exclusively within Africa": "",
  "Migration from developed to developing countries": "",
  "Since the mid-20th century, the dominant global migration flow has been from less developed countries in Latin America, Asia, and Africa to more developed countries in North America, Europe, and Oceania, driven primarily by economic disparities.": "",
  "What is a diaspora?": "",
  "A scattered population with a common origin who maintain cultural ties to their homeland": "",
  "A formal immigration agreement between countries": "",
  "A type of refugee camp": "",
  "A disease spread through migration": "",
  "A diaspora is a group of people who have spread from their original homeland to multiple locations worldwide while maintaining connections to their culture and identity. Examples include the Jewish, Armenian, Chinese, and Indian diasporas.": "",
  "What is the primary demographic effect of rural-to-urban migration on the origin area?": "",
  "Rapid population growth in rural areas": "",
  "Loss of young, working-age population, leaving behind an older and younger population": "",
  "Increased birth rates in rural areas": "",
  "No effect on rural population structure": "",
  "Rural-to-urban migration selectively removes young, working-age adults from rural areas, leaving behind an aging population and children. This increases the dependency ratio in rural areas and can lead to labor shortages in agriculture.": "",
  "What is the gravity model of migration?": "",
  "A model predicting migration based on climate within the broader context of migration analysis": "",
  "A model showing how heavy objects attract migrants, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "A model based on Earth's gravitational pull, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A model predicting that migration between two places is proportional to their populations and inversely proportional to the distance between them": "",
  "The gravity model, adapted from Newton's law, predicts that larger populations generate more migration and that migration decreases with distance. Larger cities attract more migrants, but distance (friction) reduces the flow.": "",
  "What effect does immigration typically have on the age structure of the receiving country?": "",
  "It only affects the sex ratio, not the age structure": "",
  "It has no effect on age structure": "",
  "It tends to make the population younger because immigrants are disproportionately of working age": "",
  "It makes the population older on average": "",
  "Immigrants tend to be younger and of working age, which lowers the median age of the receiving country, increases the labor force, and can help offset population aging. They also tend to have higher fertility rates initially.": "",
  "What is chain migration?": "",
  "A government program linking immigration to employment": "",
  "Migrants traveling in connected groups like a chain": "",
  "The process where established migrants help family and community members follow them to the same destination": "",
  "Migration along a chain of cities": "",
  "Chain migration occurs when immigrants who have settled in a new location help relatives and friends follow by providing information, financial assistance, housing, and social support, creating self-sustaining migration networks.": "",
  "What is counter-migration (return migration)?": "",
  "The return of migrants to their place of origin after living elsewhere": "",
  "Migration in the opposite direction of prevailing winds": "",
  "Immigration that a country tries to prevent": "",
  "Migration that violates immigration laws": "",
  "Counter-migration or return migration occurs when migrants move back to their place of origin. This can happen when conditions at home improve, when migrants retire, or when they achieve their economic goals abroad and wish to return.": "",
  "What does 'transnationalism' mean?": "",
  "The maintenance of economic, social, political, and cultural ties across national borders by migrants": "",
  "The process of becoming a citizen of a new country": "",
  "International trade between two countries": "",
  "The dissolution of national borders": "",
  "Transnationalism describes how modern migrants maintain ongoing connections to both their home and host countries through technology, travel, remittances, and dual citizenship, living in social fields that span national borders.": "",
  "What does 'net migration' mean?": "",
  "The cost of migration per person": "",
  "The total number of people who migrate internationally each year": "",
  "Migration that occurs through social networks": "",
  "The difference between the number of immigrants entering and emigrants leaving a country": "",
  "Net migration is calculated as immigration minus emigration. A positive net migration means more people are entering than leaving (net gain), while a negative net migration means more are leaving than entering (net loss).": "",
  "What does 'brain gain' mean?": "",
  "The return of all emigrants to their home country": "",
  "Improved test scores in schools": "",
  "The immigration of highly skilled and educated individuals into a country, enriching its human capital": "",
  "The increase in intelligence from education": "",
  "Brain gain is the opposite of brain drain: it occurs when a country attracts skilled immigrants, gaining human capital. Countries like the United States, Canada, and Australia benefit from brain gain by attracting talented workers and researchers globally.": "",
  "What is 'distance decay' in migration?": "",
  "The physical deterioration of roads over distance": "",
  "The emotional difficulty of being far from home": "",
  "The time it takes to travel between two places": "",
  "The principle that the volume of migration decreases as the distance between origin and destination increases": "",
  "Distance decay in migration means that as the distance between origin and destination increases, the likelihood and volume of migration decreases. This is because costs, unfamiliarity, and barriers increase with distance.": "",
  "What does 'counterstream' mean in migration?": "",
  "An immigration policy opposing the dominant trend": "",
  "A smaller flow of migrants moving in the opposite direction of the main migration stream": "",
  "Migration that goes against river currents": "",
  "Resistance to immigration by local populations": "",
  "Ravenstein observed that every migration stream generates a counterstream: a smaller flow in the opposite direction. For example, while millions migrate from Mexico to the U.S., a smaller stream of people moves from the U.S. to Mexico.": "",
  "What is 'acculturation'?": "",
  "The process by which immigrants adopt elements of the host culture while retaining aspects of their original culture": "",
  "The growth of agricultural practices in a new region": "",
  "Forcing immigrants to abandon their native language": "",
  "Rejecting the culture of a new country entirely": "",
  "Acculturation is the gradual adoption of the host culture's practices, values, and language by immigrants while often retaining elements of their heritage. It is a middle ground between full assimilation and maintaining complete cultural separation.": "",
  "What is 'assimilation'?": "",
  "The process by which immigrants fully integrate into the host society, adopting its culture and often losing their distinctive cultural identity": "",
  "Living in an ethnic enclave and avoiding contact with the host culture": "",
  "Deporting immigrants back to their home country": "",
  "The creation of bilingual education programs": "",
  "Assimilation is the process by which immigrants gradually become indistinguishable from the host population in terms of language, customs, and identity. It typically occurs over multiple generations and varies in speed depending on cultural distance and openness.": "",
  "What is an 'ethnic enclave'?": "",
  "A neighborhood or area with a high concentration of a particular ethnic group, often with businesses and institutions serving that community": "",
  "A country with only one ethnic group, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "A government office processing immigration, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A fenced border between two countries under most circumstances involving ethnic factors": "",
  "Ethnic enclaves are geographic concentrations of immigrants sharing a common ethnicity, such as Chinatowns, Little Italys, or Koreatowns. They provide social support, cultural continuity, and economic opportunities for new immigrants.": "",
  "What does 'migration stream' mean?": "",
  "Live video coverage of migration events": "",
  "A river used for transportation by migrants": "",
  "A well-established flow of migrants from a specific origin to a specific destination": "",
  "A government policy directing migration flows": "",
  "A migration stream is a consistent, well-defined pattern of movement between a particular origin and destination, such as the stream of Mexican migrants to the American Southwest or the flow of Turkish workers to Germany.": "",
  "What is 'xenophobia'?": "",
  "A fear of enclosed spaces": "",
  "A policy welcoming all immigrants": "",
  "An irrational fear or hatred of foreigners and people from other cultures": "",
  "The scientific study of migration patterns": "",
  "Xenophobia is the fear, distrust, or hatred of foreigners and people perceived as culturally different. It can manifest in discrimination, hate crimes, and restrictive immigration policies, and often intensifies during economic downturns or large migration events.": "",
  "India is the world's largest recipient of remittances, receiving over $100 billion annually. Many Indian workers in the Gulf states, United States, and United Kingdom send money home. For some Indian states like Kerala, remittances account for over 30% of the state's GDP. What does this demonstrate about the economic geography of migration?": "",
  "Only the destination country benefits from migration, since standard models of remittances behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Remittances have no significant economic impact, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing remittances dynamics": "",
  "Remittances are harmful to developing economies, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing remittances dynamics": "",
  "Migration creates transnational economic linkages where labor exported from origin regions generates financial flows that significantly reshape development at both local and national scales": "",
  "India's remittance economy demonstrates how migration creates economic linkages spanning continents. Remittances fund education, healthcare, housing, and small businesses in origin areas, sometimes exceeding foreign aid in their development impact.": "",
  "Sub-Saharan African countries lose approximately 20,000 healthcare professionals to brain drain each year. Ghana, for example, has trained doctors who leave for the UK or US where salaries are dramatically higher. Meanwhile, Ghana has only about 1 doctor per 10,000 people compared to 28 per 10,000 in the US. What does this illustrate?": "",
  "African countries should stop training doctors, since the prevailing theory about countries would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "Doctors who emigrate always return home eventually, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Brain drain worsens global health inequality by transferring human capital from countries that desperately need it to wealthy countries that already have surpluses": "",
  "Brain drain only affects technology workers, not healthcare, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Medical brain drain creates a devastating paradox: developing countries invest in training doctors who then serve wealthy countries. This worsens health outcomes in the origin country while the destination country gains skilled professionals at minimal training cost.": "",
  "Miami, Florida has been transformed by Cuban migration since 1959. The city's Little Havana neighborhood maintains Cuban culture, Spanish-language media dominates, and Cuban-Americans hold significant political power. Some argue this represents failed assimilation, while others see it as successful multiculturalism. What migration concept does Miami best exemplify?": "",
  "Temporary guest worker arrangements without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Complete assimilation of immigrants, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "The creation of a powerful ethnic enclave that reshapes the cultural, economic, and political landscape of the receiving area": "",
  "Failed migration resulting in mass return, based on conventional assumptions about Cuban": "",
  "Miami's Cuban community demonstrates how chain migration can create powerful ethnic enclaves that transform receiving areas. Rather than assimilating into existing culture, the enclave created a bilingual, bicultural metropolitan area with significant economic and political influence.": "",
  "The European Union's Schengen Area allows free movement of people across 27 European countries without border checks. A Polish worker can move to Germany for work without a visa. However, rising immigration concerns have led some countries to temporarily reinstate border controls. What tension does this represent?": "",
  "The tension between the economic benefits of free labor movement and concerns about sovereignty, security, and cultural identity": "",
  "Border controls are impossible in the modern world": "",
  "All EU countries fully support open borders": "",
  "Free movement has no economic benefits": "",
  "The Schengen Area illustrates the tension between economic integration (free labor movement boosts efficiency) and national sovereignty concerns (immigration, security, and cultural identity). This tension intensifies during refugee crises and economic downturns.": "",
  "Mexico's border region with the United States contains maquiladoras (assembly factories) that employ hundreds of thousands of workers who migrated from Mexico's interior. Many originally planned to cross into the US but settled in border cities like Ciudad Juarez instead. What migration concept does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Forced migration by the Mexican government, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Intervening opportunity, where economic opportunities along the migration route cause migrants to settle before reaching their intended destination": "",
  "Counter-urbanization patterns based on the conventional understanding of how border processes interact in practice": "",
  "Return migration to rural areas considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "Mexico's maquiladora border zone exemplifies intervening opportunity: factories along the migration route provide employment that causes many migrants to settle in border cities rather than continuing to the United States, their original intended destination.": "",
  "A Somali immigrant in Minneapolis uses WhatsApp to video-call family in Mogadishu daily, sends remittances through mobile money, votes in Somali elections from abroad, watches Somali news online, and visits Somalia every few years. She also has American citizenship and her children attend American schools. What concept does her life illustrate?": "",
  "Complete assimilation into American society in most scenarios involving Somali factors": "",
  "Failed integration requiring deportation when considering all relevant Somali factors": "",
  "Transnationalism, where modern technology enables migrants to maintain deep connections to both home and host countries simultaneously": "",
  "Temporary guest worker status because conventional analysis of Somali suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "This exemplifies transnationalism: modern communication and transportation allow migrants to live in social, economic, and political spaces spanning multiple countries simultaneously. Technology has dramatically expanded the ability to maintain transnational ties.": "",
  "Japan, facing severe labor shortages due to an aging population, has historically resisted large-scale immigration. Instead, it has invested heavily in automation and robotics. In 2019, Japan created a new visa category to admit 345,000 workers over five years, a major policy shift. What does Japan's approach reveal about the relationship between demographics and immigration policy?": "",
  "Cultural homogeneity prevents all immigration because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "Severe demographic pressures from aging and population decline can eventually force even culturally homogeneous societies to accept immigration as an economic necessity": "",
  "Robots can completely replace immigrant labor given that prevailing Japan conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "Japan will never accept immigrants due to the well-established relationship between Japan trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Japan's reluctant shift toward immigration shows that demographic realities can override cultural resistance. With a shrinking workforce threatening economic output, Japan accepted that automation alone could not fill all labor gaps, particularly in healthcare and elder care.": "",
  "After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, approximately 3.5 million East Germans moved to West Germany within a decade, attracted by higher wages and better living standards. This mass migration caused labor shortages in eastern Germany that persist decades later. What migration law does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Wall construction is the only way to prevent migration in most scenarios involving migration factors": "",
  "Major migration streams produce significant consequences for both origin and destination regions, including labor market disruption and demographic imbalances": "",
  "People never migrate within the same country, which is consistent with how migration mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "Economic factors have no influence on migration decisions, based on conventional assumptions about migration": "",
  "Post-reunification German migration shows how the removal of barriers combined with economic differentials creates massive migration streams with lasting consequences. Eastern Germany still suffers from population decline, aging, and economic disparities decades later.": "",
  "Silicon Valley in California has attracted tech workers from around the world, with immigrants founding or co-founding approximately 55% of its startups. Indian and Chinese immigrants are particularly prominent. What does this demonstrate about the relationship between migration and innovation?": "",
  "Immigration to Silicon Valley is entirely forced": "",
  "Only American-born workers contribute to Silicon Valley": "",
  "Immigration reduces innovation in destination countries": "",
  "Skilled immigration can be a major driver of innovation and economic growth, representing brain gain for the receiving country": "",
  "Silicon Valley demonstrates brain gain: the attraction of global talent drives innovation and economic growth. Immigrant entrepreneurs have founded companies like Google, Tesla, and Yahoo, showing how skilled migration can create enormous economic value for the destination.": "",
  "The Philippines has institutionalized labor export as an economic strategy, with approximately 10 million Filipino workers abroad sending home over $30 billion annually. The government operates agencies that train, place, and protect overseas workers. However, critics call this a form of 'structural dependence' on remittances. What does this case reveal?": "",
  "All Filipino workers abroad are forced migrants": "",
  "The Philippines has solved its unemployment problem completely": "",
  "Remittances always lead to sustainable development": "",
  "Labor export can generate vital revenue but may create economic dependency on remittances and mask the failure to develop domestic employment opportunities": "",
  "The Philippines illustrates both the benefits and risks of institutionalized labor migration. While remittances reduce poverty and fund education, dependence on exported labor may substitute for developing domestic industries and can separate families for years.": ""
